Node.Notes: Contrast between one with moderate means (lightly regarded and has only/at least one servant) and one pretending (honoring himself and lacks food).
Some change the vowels to yield "works for himself" (supported by LXX). MT may have sense of "and have (only/at least) one servant."
Uncertain. May be net/prey (extended to plunder)/stronghold. Either net (delights in their own evil snares/machinations) or plunder.
Uncertain. Literally, "gives." Perhaps in sense of produce (and thus being productive).
Either an evil trap or trap of an evil man.
Literally, "(As for) a fool, his vexation is known in a day (i.e., immediately)."
"Breathes out," in the sense of pouring forth.
Sense of "lying tongue lasts only a moment."
Uncertain. Among better suggestions that stick with the text and try their best to make sense of the verb are "May the righteous explore his neighbor" and "the righteous shows his neighbor the way."
Uncertain. Possibly related to Aramaic word meaning "to roast." LXX has "to catch."
Order of the words causes uncertainty. Tree here understands "the prized possession of a man (is to be) diligent."
"Way of path" and "not" are both difficult. Many change to "wickedness" and "to." Perhaps "the way of path (in the sense of a well-constructed road) has no death"?
